### Code

```kotlin
import java.time.Instant
import java.time.temporal.ChronoUnit
import kotlin.math.abs

fun formatTimeAgo(instant: Instant): String {
 val now = Instant.now()
 val minutesAgo = ChronoUnit.MINUTES.between(instant, now)
 val hoursAgo = ChronoUnit.HOURS.between(instant, now)
 val daysAgo = ChronoUnit.DAYS.between(instant, now)
 val weeksAgo = daysAgo / 7
 val monthsAgo = daysAgo / 30
 val yearsAgo = daysAgo / 365

 return when {
 yearsAgo > 0 -> "$yearsAgo year${if (yearsAgo > 1) "s" else ""} ago"
 monthsAgo > 0 -> "$monthsAgo month${if (monthsAgo > 1) "s" else ""} ago"
 weeksAgo > 0 -> "$weeksAgo week${if (weeksAgo > 1) "s" else ""} ago"
 daysAgo > 0 -> "$daysAgo day${if (daysAgo > 1) "s" else ""} ago"
 hoursAgo > 0 -> "$hoursAgo hour${if (hoursAgo > 1) "s" else ""} ago"
 minutesAgo > 0 -> "$minutesAgo minute${if (minutesAgo > 1) "s" else ""} ago"
 else -> "just now"
 }
}
```

### Usage

```kotlin
val pastInstant = Instant.now().minus(5, ChronoUnit.DAYS)
println(formatTimeAgo(pastInstant))
```

This function first calculates the difference between the current time and the provided `Instant` in various units (minutes, hours, days, weeks, months, years). It then returns a formatted string based on these differences. The function uses simple division for weeks, months, and years to keep the calculation straightforward, though more complex logic could be used for more accurate month and year calculations considering varying month lengths","referencedFilePaths":null,"imageFilePath":null,"webSearchIncluded":false,"documentationDetails":null,"personaName":null},{"prompt":"ChronoUnit is not at the kotlin date time library anymore, what should i use ?
